r granted in many parts of the world.  This utopian view is rapidly changing; however, as greater demands are placed on what is fast becoming a limited resource. As experts publicly debate the impact of global warming on climatic conditions, drought and local water shortages, the general public's awareness of these problems is increased.  And as concerns over water quality issues grow, government regulatory controls expand in an attempt to resolve conflicts caused by water shortages, restrictions on use and owners' rights...corrosion in copper pipes can be preventedby William Harfst, Water Technology Magazine, Vol 22, Issue 3 1999Copper pipe is used extensively for residential, commercial and industrial water service. It offers superior corrosion resistance, is durable and easy to work, and provides excellent heat transfer. However, under certain operating environments, problems can develop, such as pinhole leaks, failures at soldered joints, elevated copper and lead levels in water and general corrosion failure. Repeated corrosion failures of this type are aggravating and expensive. Fortunately, these problems are easy to identify...If you use water, we're good people to know...I have worked with hundreds of companies to implement the strategies discussed in these articles.  The same opportunities are available to you.Other NewsBill is the author of two monthly technical columns entitled Back to Basics in Ultrapure Water Journal and Waterside Fundamentals in Industrial Water Treatment.  Contact me if you would like copies of these articles.Contact us today!We welcome your questions and queries. Please see our Contact Us page for complete contact information.Copyright Harfst and Associates, inc. All rights reserved. Web Hosting by Yahoo! P.O. Box 276Crystal Lake, IL 60039ph: (815) 861-9082fax: (815) 477-7824wfh@mc.net  
